(40, 13, 1, 40, 13, 1, 15, 'sat by the sea side', 'Jesus Teaching by the Sea', 'This connection highlights Jesus'' action of sitting by the sea, which serves as the setting for his teaching. The gathering of multitudes and his subsequent parables emphasize the importance of the location in conveying his message.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 1, 41, 4, 1, 12, 'sat by the sea side', 'Teaching by the Sea', 'This connection highlights Jesus teaching by the sea in both passages. Matthew 13:1 mentions Jesus sitting by the sea side, while Mark 4:1 describes him teaching a multitude gathered by the sea.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 1, 40, 13, 36, 36, NULL, 'Jesus'' Movement Between Locations', 'This connection highlights Jesus'' transition from the sea side to the house, emphasizing his teaching environment. Both passages illustrate the shift in setting as he engages with the multitude and later with his disciples.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 1, 41, 2, 13, 13, 'by the sea side', 'Teaching by the Sea', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus teaching by the sea side, highlighting his ministry''s connection to this location. The mention of the sea side in both verses suggests a thematic link in his teaching activities.', 'theme', 0.293, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 2, 42, 5, 3, 3, 'he went into a ship', 'Teaching from a Ship', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus teaching from a ship. In Matthew, he sits in a ship due to the crowd, while in Luke, he enters Simon''s ship to teach the people.', 'parallel', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 2, 1, 49, 10, 10, NULL, 'Gathering of the People', 'This connection highlights the theme of gathering. In Matthew, the multitude gathers to Jesus, while Genesis speaks of the gathering of people to Shiloh, indicating a significant leader.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 2, 40, 4, 25, 25, 'great multitudes were gathered together', 'Gathering of Great Multitudes', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of great multitudes following Jesus. In Matthew 4:25, the multitudes are identified as coming from various regions, while Matthew 13:2 describes them gathering to hear him speak.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 2, 40, 15, 30, 30, 'great multitudes were gathered together', 'Gathering of Great Multitudes', 'Both passages emphasize the gathering of great multitudes around Jesus, highlighting his role as a focal point for those in need. In Matthew 13:2, the multitude is drawn to him, while in Matthew 15:30, they come bringing the afflicted for healing.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 2, 41, 4, 1, 1, NULL, 'Teaching by the Sea', 'Both passages emphasize a great multitude gathered to hear Jesus teach by the sea. The descriptions of Jesus entering a ship and the crowd standing on the shore are nearly identical, highlighting the setting of his teaching.', 'parallel', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 2, 42, 8, 4, 8, 'great multitudes were gathered together', 'Gathering of the Multitude', 'Both passages emphasize the gathering of large crowds to hear Jesus. In Matthew, the multitude is described as ''great,'' while in Luke, people come ''out of every city'' to listen. This connection highlights the significance of Jesus'' teaching moments.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 3, 41, 4, 2, 9, 'a sower went forth to sow', 'Parable of the Sower Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the parable of the sower, illustrating the different outcomes of the seeds based on the soil they fall on. The phrase ''a sower went forth to sow'' appears in both, linking their messages about receptivity to teaching.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 3, 41, 4, 13, 13, 'a sower went forth to sow', 'Connection of Parables in Gospels', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of understanding parables. Matthew introduces the parable of the sower, while Mark highlights the necessity of grasping this parable to comprehend others.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 3, 10, 12, 1, 7, NULL, 'Parables and Moral Lessons', 'Both passages emphasize the use of storytelling to convey moral truths. In Matthew, Jesus uses a parable about a sower, while Nathan employs a narrative to reveal David''s wrongdoing. This connection highlights the method of teaching through relatable stories.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 3, 19, 78, 2, 2, NULL, 'Connection of Parables in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the use of parables to convey deeper meanings. Matthew introduces the sower parable, while Psalms indicates the speaker will use parables to express profound truths.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 3, 26, 24, 3, 14, 'spake many things unto them in parables', 'Parables of Judgment and Consequence', 'Both passages emphasize the use of parables to convey messages of judgment. In Matthew, the sower represents the act of spreading a message, while Ezekiel''s pot serves as a metaphor for the consequences of rebellion. This connection highlights the theme of divine communication through imagery.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 3, 40, 13, 10, 13, 'a sower went forth to sow', 'Parables and Understanding', 'Both passages emphasize the use of parables to convey deeper meanings. The first introduces the sower parable, while the second explains why parables are used, highlighting the distinction between those who understand and those who do not.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 3, 40, 13, 34, 35, 'spake many things unto them in parables', 'Connection of Parables in Matthew', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus speaking in parables. The first introduces the sower parable, while the second highlights that Jesus spoke only in parables, fulfilling prophecy.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 4, 40, 13, 18, 19, NULL, 'Connection of the Sower''s Seed', 'This connection highlights the fate of the seeds that fell by the way side. Both passages emphasize how the wicked one comes and takes away what was sown in the heart, illustrating the lack of understanding of the word of the kingdom.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 5, 26, 11, 19, 19, 'stony places', 'Connection of Stony Hearts', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''stony'' conditions. In Matthew, the stony places hinder growth, while Ezekiel speaks of removing a stony heart to allow for transformation.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 5, 26, 36, 26, 26, 'stony', 'Connection of Stony Hearts', 'This connection highlights the theme of ''stony'' conditions in the heart. In Matthew, the ''stony places'' hinder growth, while Ezekiel speaks of replacing a ''stony heart'' with a ''heart of flesh,'' suggesting transformation.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 5, 38, 7, 12, 12, 'stony places', 'Connection of Stony Hearts', 'This connection highlights the theme of hardness of heart. In Matthew, the seed''s inability to take root reflects a lack of depth, while in Zechariah, the adamant stone symbolizes a refusal to hear God''s words.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 5, 30, 6, 12, 12, 'not much earth', 'Connection of Stony Ground and Judgment', 'This connection highlights the theme of unfruitfulness in challenging soil. Both passages emphasize the lack of depth and the consequences of poor foundations, whether in faith or in justice.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 5, 40, 13, 20, 20, 'stony places', 'Connection of Stony Places', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''stony places'' where the seed is received. The first verse describes the conditions of the soil, while the second illustrates the immediate reception of the word in those same conditions.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 6, 40, 13, 21, 21, 'had no root', 'Connection of Root and Tribulation', 'Both passages emphasize the lack of root, leading to failure under pressure. The first verse illustrates how plants without roots wither, while the second describes individuals who, lacking root, falter during tribulation.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 6, 59, 1, 11, 12, 'withered away', 'Endurance in Trials', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of enduring hardship. The imagery of withering due to the sun in Matthew parallels the fate of the rich man in James, highlighting the transient nature of worldly success. This connection highlights the importance of perseverance in the face of trials.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 6, 23, 49, 10, 10, NULL, 'Connection of Scorching and Protection', 'Both passages emphasize the effects of heat and sun on those without protection. Matthew describes how the sun scorches the unrooted, while Isaiah promises that the heat shall not smite those led by mercy.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 6, 42, 8, 13, 13, 'no root', 'Connection of Root and Scorching', 'Both passages emphasize the lack of root leading to withering or falling away. The imagery of being scorched in Matthew parallels the idea of those who believe temporarily but ultimately fail in Luke.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 6, 49, 3, 17, 17, NULL, 'Rootedness in Faith and Love', 'This connection highlights the importance of being ''rooted'' in faith and love. While Matthew discusses the consequences of lacking roots, Ephesians emphasizes being ''rooted and grounded'' in love, suggesting a foundational aspect of spiritual growth.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 6, 51, 1, 23, 23, 'no root', 'Faith and Rootedness Connection', 'This connection highlights the importance of being ''grounded and settled'' in faith to avoid spiritual withering, as seen in the warning of those who ''had no root'' and withered away. Both passages emphasize the necessity of a strong foundation to withstand challenges.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 6, 40, 7, 26, 27, 'no root', 'Connection of Foundation and Stability', 'Both passages emphasize the consequences of a lack of stability. The ''no root'' in Matthew 13:6 parallels the ''built his house upon the sand'' in Matthew 7:26, illustrating the fragility of faith without a solid foundation.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
